Figures \ref{smoothnon} and \ref{smoothsol} show the the seasonal trends in in power bill for regular power and solar power. Regular power bills are much higher for June through September; Solar power bills are greater from November through February. We create a "peak season" indicator variable to allow for different power bill prices for the respective peak season months given solar and regular power. We fit a cell means model for each combination of Solar power status and the peak season indicator. Thus our $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ vector is a vector of means for each combination. The is model written as follows:
$$
\mathrm{Y} = \mathtt{Solar0:Peak0} \mu_1 + \mathtt{Solar0:Peak1} \mu_2 + \mathtt{Solar1:Peak0} \mu_3 + \mathtt{Solar1:Peak1} \mu_4 + \epsilon
$$
where $\epsilon|\mathtt{Solar}$ has an autoregressive correlation structure with parameters $\sigma^2$ and $\rho$. Thus we assume that the times series for the power bills for solar and non solar are independent of each other. This assumption is not unreasonable since we adjust for the the peak season effect for solar and non solar power bills.

