 These assumptions however are hard to verify given that we only have one correlated observation. So to check the assumptions we can 'decorrelate' the model using the lower cholesky decomposition of the covariance matrix of the original model, $\sigma^{2} \mathbf{R}$. Once decorrelated, we use plots of the residuals to verify the assumptions of constant variance, and normally distributed residuals. Figures \ref{resplot} and \ref{reshist} show the plot of fitted values vs residuals and the distribution of the residuals respectively. The plots show that the variance isn't really constant, and that the residuals don't appear to be approximately normally distributed. (It turns out that by accounting for a seasonal effect and due to the limited amount of data, there doesn't appear to be any significant correlation. However, for the sake of completing this as a correlated data analysis we chose to proceed, even though the assumptions don't really hold.) We also used this decorrelated model to get an $R^2$ value to assess the fit of our model. The resulting $R^2$ value of 0.8057 tells us that 80\% of the variance in monthly power bill payment is explained by our model. The goodness of fit can be visualized in figure \ref{modfit} which shows the fitted model plotted along with the observed data. We conclude that our model fits the data well, especially considering that we have relatively limited data. 

