Figure \ref{future:pred} shows the estimated savings for each month into the future from switching to solar and corresponding 95\% prediction intervals. The cyclical pattern of the estimated savings is due to the choice of our model, with different seasonal effects for solar and non solar. Customers save less during winter months when the difference between solar and regular power bills is less and save much more in summer months when regular power bills rise and solar power bills drop. To date the consumer has saved an estimated \$2000, with a 95\% prediction interval of (\$1763.75,\$2236.94). In just under two years, the costumer has regained a quarter of their initial investment through savings from switching to solar power. 

We are also interested in the number of additional months until the customer regains their total investment for switching to solar power. The blue lines in figure \ref{future:pred} correspond to the estimated number years and prediction intervals after switching to solar until the constumer regains their \$8000 dollar investment. It is estimated that it will take an additional 70 months (5.8 years) from February 2018 for solar power to pay for itself. This brings the total estimated time for solar to pay for itself to be 7 years and 8 months with a lower bound of the 95\% prediction interval 7 years and 2 months and the upper bound 8 years and 3 months. The width of this interval is only a year wide, which is a a very good interval estimate for the amount of time it takes for solar to pay for itself. 


\section{Conclusion}
% Did the report summarize how the goals of the study were met?
% Did the report discuss any shortcomings of the approach/model used?
% Did the report provide suggestions for 'next steps' in the analysis or further questions that may be of interest?
The intial goals of this analysis were to determine how much money per month on average a customer can save by switching to solar power, and to determine the amount of time at which a customer will recoup the initial cost of \$8000 solar power equipment. From this analysis we determined that a customer will save approximately \$160 per month during summer months, and \$21 a month during winter months. This ends up as an overall average savings of about \$90 per month. Additionally, we conclude that it will take approximately 7 years and 8 months for a customer to recoup the cost of converting to solar power. These findings will be helpful for solar companies to promote the benfits of solar power, and will help potential customers to financially prepare when converting to solar power. Some shortcomings of this analysis include the limited amount of data available, and the lack of a strong correlation in the data. We only have data from one customer in one location which limits the ability to scale our conclusions. This analysis could be improved after gathering data for a longer period of time, and for multiple customers. It may also be interesting to assess the effectiveness of solar power for different regions by comparing rate-adjusted savings on power bills for customer in different regions.

 
